<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" label="de-components">
	<title> Differential Equation Components </title>

	<introduction label="de-components-intro">
		<p>
			Now that you can recognize a differential equation, it‚Äôs time to look more closely at what it‚Äôs made of. In this section, we‚Äôll break down the core components of a differential equation and explain the role each one plays in shaping it.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs label="variables">
		<title> Dependent and Independent Variables </title>
		<p>
			Every differential equation involves dependent and independent variables. The <term>dependent variable</term> is a function that depends on the <term>independent variable</term> and is the unknown function we're solving for. Because of this, the dependent variable always has derivatives applied to it‚Äîwith respect to the independent variable.
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-variables-1"><title> üéØ Which Variable has the Derivative </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					In a differential equation, you would expect to see a derivative applied to the dependent variable.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							True
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The dependent variable in a differential equation always has a derivative applied to it.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							False
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. By definition, a differential equation involves derivatives of the dependent variable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<p>
			For example, the differential equation:
			<men xml:id="variables-de-1">
				\frac{dy}{dx} + 2y = 4x^2.
			</men>
			has <m>y</m> as the dependent variable‚Äîit‚Äôs the unknown function. Since the equation includes <m>dy/dx</m>, that tells us <m>y</m> is changing with respect to <m>x</m>, making <m>x</m> the independent variable.
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-variables-2"><title> üéØ Dependent vs. Independent </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which variable in the differential equation,
					<me>
						\frac{dP}{ds} + \frac{P}{s^2} = 17s
					</me>,
					represents the unknown function we would like to find?
				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<choices>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						dependent variable, <m>s</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. <m>s</m> is neither the dependent variable, nor what we are solving for.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						independent variable, <m>s</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect! <m>s</m> is the independent variable, but it is not what we are solving for.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						dependent variable, <m>P</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Yes! We are solving for the unknown, <m>P</m> which is the dependent variable in this equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						independent variable, <m>P</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. We are solving for <m>P</m>, but it is not the independent variable.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

			</choices>

		</task>

		<p>
			Identifying the dependent variable not only tells us what we're solving for, but it will also be an important part of determining which methods can be used to solve a differential equation.
		</p>

		<example>
			<title> Identify the Variables </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Identify the dependent and independent variable in each equation:
					<me>
						\frac{dP}{ds} + \frac{P}{s^2} = 17s,\qquad
						u'' + t^2 u = 0,\qquad
						Q'' = 11Q
					</me>
					
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The first equation contains <m>P</m> and <m>s</m>, but the presence of <m>dP/ds</m> implies <m>P</m> changes as <m>s</m> changes. So,
					<ul>
						<li><m>P</m> is the <em>unknown</em> function we solve for that depends on <m>s</m>.</li>
						<li><em>dependent variable</em> <m>\rightarrow P</m> , <em>independent variable</em> <m>\rightarrow s</m> .</li>
					</ul>
				</p>

				<p>
					The middle equation contains <m>u</m> and <m>t</m>, but <m>u''</m> is the second derivative of <m>u</m>. So, <m>u</m> must change as <m>t</m> changes and
					<ul>
						<li><m>u</m> is the <em>unknown</em> function we solve for that depends on <m>t</m>.</li>
						<li><em>dependent variable</em> <m>\rightarrow u</m> , <em>independent variable</em> <m>\rightarrow t</m> .</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			
				<p>
					Only <m>Q</m> appears in the last equation, but <m>Q''</m> indicates that <m>Q</m> is changing and so it must be the <em>dependent variable</em>. Typically, the independent variable will be clear from context of the problem, but in this case just assume whatever variable you like.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<task label="chkpt-variables-3">
			<title> üéØ Identify the Unknown </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						For each differential equation, identify the variable that represents the solution
					</p>
					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="5% 30% 20%" margins="20% 20%" valign="middle">
							<p><m>1.</m></p>
							<p><me>tm' + t^2 = 0</me></p>
							<p>Answer: <fillin width="2" mode="string" answer="m" /></p>
						</sidebyside>
					</p>
					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="5% 30% 20%" margins="20% 20%" valign="middle">
							<p><m>2.</m></p>
							<p><me>Q^2 - 11Q = P''</me></p>
							<p>Answer: <fillin width="2" mode="string" answer="P" /></p>
						</sidebyside>
					</p>
					<p>
						<sidebyside widths="5% 30% 20%" margins="20% 20%" valign="middle">
							<p><m>3.</m></p>
							<p><me>\frac{dx}{dy} = 2xy + 1</me></p>
							<p>Answer: <fillin width="2" mode="string" answer="x" /></p>
						</sidebyside>
					</p>
				</statement>
				
				<evaluation>
					<evaluate>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*m\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Yes, the solution to the differential equation is the dependent variable <m>m</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*M\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No, <m>M</m> is not the same as <m>m</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*t\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No, <m>t</m> is what the solution depends on, but it is not the solution itself.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Incorrect. Carefully review the reading and try again.</feedback>
						</test>
					</evaluate>
					<evaluate>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*P\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Yes, the solution to the differential equation is the dependent variable <m>P</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*p\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No, <m>p</m> is not the same as <m>P</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*Q\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No. Carefully look at which variable has the derivative applied to it.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Incorrect. That's not a variable in the equation.</feedback>
						</test>
					</evaluate>
					<evaluate>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*x\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Yes, the solution to the differential equation is the dependent variable <m>x</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*X\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No, <m>X</m> is not the same as <m>x</m>.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>\s*y\s*</strcmp>
							<feedback>No. Carefully look at which variable has the derivative applied to it.</feedback>
						</test>
						<test>
							<strcmp>.*</strcmp>
							<feedback>Incorrect. That's not a variable in the equation.</feedback>
						</test>
					</evaluate>
				</evaluation>
		</task>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="terms-of-a-de" xml:id="terms">
		<title> Terms of a Differential Equation </title>

		<p>
			The word <q>term</q> is commonly used to describe a part of a mathematical expression. In a differential equation, a <term>term</term> refers to any part of the expression separated by plus (<m>+</m>) or minus (<m>-</m>) signs. For example, an equation might be structured like this:
			<me>
				\text{term}\ 1 + \text{term}\ 2 - \text{term}\ 3 = \text{term}\ 4 - \text{term}\ 5.
			</me>
			This equation has three terms on the left-hand side and two on the right.

		</p>

		<p>
			Terms may include the dependent variable, its derivatives, constants, or other functions of the independent variable. If a term does <em>not</em> include the dependent variable or its derivatives, it is called a <term>constant term</term>. For instance, in the differential equation:
		</p>

		<me>
			\frac{3}{x} y^{(6)} + 5.3 y'' + x^2 (y'-4)^3 - y = \frac12\ln(x)
		</me>

		<p>
			the terms break down as follows:
		</p>
		
		<p>
			<tabular halign="center">
				<row>
					<cell bottom="minor"><m>y^{(6)}</m> term</cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell bottom="minor"><m>y''</m> term</cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell bottom="minor"><m>(y'-4)^3</m> term</cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell bottom="minor"><m>y</m> term</cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell bottom="minor">constant term</cell>
				</row>
				<row><cell/></row>
				<row>
					<cell><m>\ds \frac{3}{x} y^{(6)}</m></cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell><m>\ds 5.3 y''</m></cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell><m>\ds x^2 (y'-4)^3</m></cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell><m>\ds -y</m></cell>
					<cell/>
					<cell><m>\ds \frac12\ln(x)</m></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-terms-1">
			<title> üéØ What is the Constant Term? </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Identify the constant term in the differential equation
					<me>3t^2 y' - 4t^2 = \frac{1}{t} y.</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 3t^2 y'</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. This term contains a derivative of the dependent variable <m>y</m>, so it is not a constant term.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad \ds\frac{1}{t} y</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. This term involves the dependent variable <m>y</m>, so it is not a constant term.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 4t^2</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Correct! <m>4t^2</m> is the constant term because it does not contain the dependent variable <m>y</m>.
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<p>
			Every differential equation has a constant term, even if it‚Äôs not written explicitly. For example, <m>y' = -3y</m> can be rewritten as <m>y' + 3y = 0</m>, where the constant term is <m>0</m>. In general, any missing term can always be interpreted as a zero term.
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-terms-2">
			<title> üéØ Hidden Constant Term </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Identify the constant term of the differential equation
					<me>w''=3tw.</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 3tw</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. This term involves the dependent variable <m>w</m>, so it is not a constant term.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 3t</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. This term involves the dependent variable <m>w</m>, so it is not a constant term.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 0</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Correct! The constant term is <m>0</m> because we can rewrite the equation as <m>w'' - 3tw = 0</m>.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice>
					<statement>
						This equation does not have a constant term.
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. Every DE has a least one constant term.
					</feedback>
				</choice>

			</choices>
		</task>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="coefficients-of-a-de" xml:id="coefficients">
		<title> Coefficients of a Differential Equation </title>

		<p>
			A <term>coefficient</term> in a differential equation is a constant or function (depending only on the independent variable) that multiplies the dependent variable or one of its derivatives. Coefficients help determine the structure of the equation and what solution methods are possible.
		</p>

		<p>
			For example, in the equation:
			<men xml:id="example-coefficients-of-a-de-1">
				y'' - 3y' + 2y = 0,
			</men>
			the coefficients of <m>y''</m>, <m>y'</m>, and <m>y</m> are the constants <m>1</m>, <m>-3</m>, and <m>2</m>, respectively.
		</p>

		<p>
			Coefficients can also be functions of the independent variable. In the equation:
			<me>
			t^2 y'' + 5t y' + 6y = \sin(t),
			</me>
			the coefficients are the functions of the independent variable <m>t</m>:
		</p>

		<p>
			<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell><m>\ul{y''\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y'\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ul{y\text{ coefficient}}</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m>t^2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>5t</m></cell>
				<cell><m>6</m></cell>
			</row>
			</tabular>
		</p>

		<task label="chkpt-terms-coeffs-1a"><title> üéØ Coefficient of <m>y'</m> </title>
			<statement>	
				<p>
					Identify the coefficient of <m>y'</m> in the differential equation
					<me>5y'' + 2\cos(t)y' - y = 7</me>
				</p>	
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad \cos(t)</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect, <m>\cos(t)</m> is only part of the coefficient of <m>y'</m>.
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 2\cos(t)</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Correct! <m>2\cos(t)</m> is the coefficient of the term involving <m>y'</m>.
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 2</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect, <m>2</m> is only part of the coefficient of <m>y'</m>.
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<m>\quad 7</m>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						Incorrect. <m>7</m> is the constant on the right-hand side of the equation.
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<p>
			In general, for something to be considered a coefficient, it must not involve the dependent variable. If it does, the equation is nonlinear, and the notion of a "coefficient" becomes less useful. We'll explore this idea further when we study linear and nonlinear equations.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

